WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Open Source Data Science in the Enterprise

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:20.799
Just over the past few years, there have been enormous advances in data analytic capabilities.

00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:26.400
The advances in the tools are enormous, but most of the energy is on the open source side of things.

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:30.400
Commercial software development is, of course, constrained by the amount of resources that any

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:36.400
individual company can put into them, whereas on the open source side, there's just the entire

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:43.840
community contributes to development of new capabilities and new tools, in addition to a lot

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:50.560
of professional support from the big tech companies for open source, which is growing by the day.

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:57.599
So you get access to really cutting-edge analytical tools because you use open source.

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:04.320
The other interesting thing is that you get access in the open source community to tools and

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:11.120
capabilities developed in other domains. Whatever domain you are in, maybe it's environmental

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:17.760
sciences or health care, you can get access to tools and packages that were developed for

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:24.879
financial services or vice versa, and you see that kind of cross-fermentation really

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:34.320
power the open source communities. Many of the most widely used and powerful analytical packages

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:41.279
work across multiple languages. TensorFlow is a good example. That is a powerful machine learning

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:48.959
framework that was developed by Google. It's open source, and it's available in all of the

00:01:48.959 --> 00:01:55.839
major open source languages, R and Python, to name the two main ones. So people can use the tools

00:01:55.839 --> 00:02:01.599
they like to achieve the results in the languages they like, knowing that there's consistency

00:02:02.639 --> 00:02:10.080
in terms of the underlying algorithms and operation of all these packages. Finally,

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:16.160
code-based analytics make it easy to see the flow of the analysis, and it's essentially self-auditing.

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:20.800
In highly regulated businesses like health care and financial services, where I came from,

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:22.000
this can be a lifesaver.

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:31.839
Open source is absolutely appropriate for enterprise-level data science.

00:02:31.839 --> 00:02:36.320
It's a great way to boost productivity as it can empower all the interested

00:02:36.800 --> 00:02:42.880
parties in the organization. At my company, there were many people that I, as a senior manager,

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:49.199
didn't even know about who were working on developing projects using open source tools.

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:56.080
So you can let a thousand flowers bloom. Now, importantly, such freedom can be done with

00:02:56.080 --> 00:03:02.720
enterprise-level curation. You can do this in a controlled way. Now, of course, IT likes that

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:06.800
because you don't have a million people launching different things which are

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:15.759
unaudited or unvalidated, but you can still have the same creativity of the team.

00:03:16.639 --> 00:03:22.720
Tools like RStudio really help provide this full production life cycle within a curated

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:30.479
environment that is enterprise-grade. There are so many people contributing to that community.

00:03:30.479 --> 00:03:35.759
There are so many tremendous packages out there. You can be comfortable that if you're using a

00:03:35.759 --> 00:03:41.119
commercial software that has been audited and vetted and has gone through a process before

00:03:41.119 --> 00:03:46.240
it was released into the wild, that is greater than what might happen in the open source community.

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:52.240
But at the same time, in the open source community, the crowdsourcing and the enormous

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:58.000
number of people that are contributing means that the quantity of tremendous enterprise-level

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:05.360
packages or tools is much, much larger. There are tools that can help companies

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:10.240
curate, audit, and validate all of those tools that are out there. Packages like RStudio

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:19.920
let you do that and have a walled garden where the appropriateness and quality of all the packages

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:23.279
is monitored within the organization.

00:04:28.399 --> 00:04:34.160
My personal experience, building support for open source software in an organization means

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:40.959
starting small. What is very powerful, I think, are small, gee-whiz demonstration projects.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.959
Take this in small bites, projects with quick turnaround that demonstrate value. Then you're

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:54.959
going to have people looking over your shoulder saying, how can I do that? So you don't have to

00:04:54.959 --> 00:05:00.799
start out with a large investment. But in my experience, the power of these tools is such that

00:05:00.799 --> 00:05:07.359
you very quickly have people saying they want in. They want to try to do some of this stuff

00:05:07.359 --> 00:05:13.440
themselves. So you obviously don't want the appearance of going rogue in your organization

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:23.200
and rejecting IT standards. But very quickly, you will find that you develop IT buy-in. I think as

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:29.279
the years have gone by, that's much, much easier to do. I think certainly within our organization,

00:05:29.279 --> 00:05:35.359
when I first started getting involved in this stuff, there wasn't a lot of IT support. But by

00:05:35.359 --> 00:05:43.600
the time I left my organization, IT was a major sponsor of open source tools because they knew

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:51.440
that they could make sure that anything that was allowed inside the organization did meet our

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:52.480
quality standards.

00:05:56.959 --> 00:06:03.359
Certainly not. Executives don't need to know how to code to manage a data science team. I was a coder

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:10.959
and it did help me be a champion with some credibility in the organization. But it's

00:06:10.959 --> 00:06:15.839
absolutely not necessary. And you can't really expect that or make that a requirement.

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:21.519
You know, the higher you go in any organization, the more you are going to be responsible for

00:06:21.519 --> 00:06:29.200
supervising people who are experts in their domain and know more about that than you do.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:37.760
I was a CEO. And of course, as most CEOs do, I was promoted through a particular business vertical,

00:06:38.799 --> 00:06:44.720
in my case, investments. That's what I had expertise in. But I didn't know anything or I

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:52.720
didn't have any particular expertise in sales or legal and certainly not IT. So an executive

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:59.200
doesn't need to be fluent in all topics and indeed cannot be. But it helps to be conversant. And some

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:06.640
of that is learning on the job. But to do that, at a minimum, you need to be curious. So you will

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:12.880
have lots of people who work for you who will know things you don't and you have to be respectful of

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:19.440
their knowledge. And you need to listen to those people who are coming in and telling you what

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:25.920
needs to be done and listen with an open mind. Ultimately, the leader has to make the decision,

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:33.279
but you want to make it with the best possible input from your teams and being respectful when

00:07:33.279 --> 00:07:39.600
someone says, I don't think this is a good idea. But again, leadership is about making the call

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:48.640
at the end of the day. But you have to be very mindful of where the expertise lies in your

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:53.839
organization. And that applies in all areas, of course, including leading data science teams.

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:07.839
I got started in R about 2006. So that's 15 years ago, I became frustrated with the limitations of

00:08:07.839 --> 00:08:14.880
Excel. I felt I had taken it as far as I could. One of the things that really bugged me was how

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:20.480
my current self had no idea what my past self did when I opened a spreadsheet from a year or two

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:27.839
prior. So how do I remember where the critical dependencies are across multiple sheets? What

00:08:27.839 --> 00:08:35.039
does this formula do? All of these things became very opaque in some of the really big, complicated

00:08:35.039 --> 00:08:42.080
spreadsheets that I did. I liked the idea of open source tools. So I discovered and started working

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:47.679
with R. And I started working with one toe in the water. I was moving back and forth with Excel,

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:54.719
importing and exporting data, using some macro tools to manage that. But as the months went on,

00:08:54.719 --> 00:09:02.320
I used Excel less and less because I got more fluent with R and found that I was getting

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:13.359
answers faster and getting answers with reusable code much more frequently. So I eventually just

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:21.200
Excel just sort of withered away and I stopped using it. And even when I became a CEO, obviously

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:27.679
playing around with spreadsheets or R wasn't part of my day job. But I'd like to keep my

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:33.200
self sharp in terms of working with R. And this had a good corporate purpose because it helped me

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:41.039
be an evangelist for R within my own organization. And again, by the time I left the company,

00:09:41.039 --> 00:09:51.280
these open source tools were an everyday part of analytics across just about all of the verticals

00:09:51.280 --> 00:10:03.919
in my company. The power of these tools is so, so large, and it's so easy to find

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:13.520
really cool examples of what you can do with these tools. It doesn't take very much digging.

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:19.599
And certainly, if you look at some of the examples in the R studio gallery,

00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:27.280
you see all sorts of stuff, all sorts of gee whiz little projects and dashboards and tools

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:35.200
that for me immediately made me think, wow, yeah, yeah, that could solve a problem I have,

00:10:35.200 --> 00:10:39.440
or that would be a great way to present some of the information that's specific to my domain,

00:10:40.239 --> 00:10:47.359
even if the information or the data set isn't relevant to my job. So it's very easy to find

00:10:47.359 --> 00:10:58.080
things that are very exciting to help advance data science in any organization. And it's still

00:10:58.080 --> 00:11:04.799
early going on the power of data science in many organizations. There are many organizations, even

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:12.080
very sophisticated quantitative analytic organizations that haven't gone after the

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:20.960
low-hanging fruit that data science has brought to fruition in the last few years. I'm speaking

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:31.119
from experience on this. So, you know, once the ball gets rolling, it's very easy to keep it going.

